<pdd-dependency>agentic_common_python.prompt</pdd-dependency>
<pdd-dependency>checkup_review_loop_python.prompt</pdd-dependency>
<pdd-dependency>checkup_gates_python.prompt</pdd-dependency>

1) This module acts as the multi-step agentic orchestrator for the `pdd checkup` command, responsible for managing an 8-step workflow that analyzes, fixes, and verifies software issues. It coordinates between LLM-based agents, local environment execution, and git state management, ensuring that changes are isolated in worktrees and that the workflow can be resumed gracefully after interruptions.

2) Requirements:
    1. Implement an 8-step workflow: 1. Discover, 2. Deps, 3. Build, 4. Interfaces, 5. Test, 6. Fix (split into 6.1 Fix, 6.2 Regression, 6.3 E2E), 7. Verify, and 8. Create PR.
    2. Manage an iterative "Fix-Verify" loop for steps 3-7; if Step 7 does not contain the string "All Issues Fixed", the workflow should loop back to Step 3, up to a maximum of `MAX_FIX_VERIFY_ITERATIONS` (default 3). If the maximum is reached without that exact signal, return failure and do not push fixes or create/skip through a successful PR gate.
       **Issue #1212 — fixer-skip, scope, causal, clean-run, and Step 5 visibility guards (PR mode only)**:
       - **Step 5 failure visibility**: when Step 5 reports failure, the orchestrator MUST print the agent's raw failure output to the console even in `--quiet` mode and pass the same text into Step 6's prompt context (`context["step5_output"]`). Route the output through `_scrub_secrets` + `_redact_secret(_, _github_token_from_env())` before printing or persisting — pytest output, command stderr, and CI logs can embed `ghp_`/`ghs_` tokens, `Bearer` headers, AWS keys, Slack tokens, or `https://user:token@host` URLs. Step 5 prompt MUST require a structured ```failure_signal``` block (command, exit_code, status, failing_ids, artifact_path, redacted raw output) so Step 6 receives concrete pytest output rather than a summary. The orchestrator parses that block via `_parse_failure_signal_block`. When `status` indicates `fail`/`error`/`failed`/`failure`, an empty `exit_code`, `failing_ids`, `artifact_path`, or `output` field counts as missing — a structurally present but content-free block is just as useless to Step 6 as a missing one. Whenever any required key is missing/empty the orchestrator synthesises a normalised ```failure_signal``` block from the scrubbed raw output, stores it in `context["step5_failure_signal"]` (with the missing-key set in `context["step5_failure_signal_missing"]`), and the Step 6.1 prompt template MUST reference both placeholders so the fixer always sees structured context — never just `{step5_output}`. When the provider reports success but the parsed `status` is a logical failure (`fail`/`error`/etc.), the orchestrator MUST still print the scrubbed failure detail to the console UNCONDITIONALLY — even in `--quiet` mode — mirroring the provider-failure path; gating that print behind `if not quiet` leaves quiet automation (the common case) with no concrete failing-test context for exactly the branch this contract added (external review PR #1215 Finding 3). Because `context` persists across fix-verify iterations, `context["step5_failure_signal"]`/`context["step5_failure_signal_missing"]` are written ONLY on the failing Step 5 path; the orchestrator MUST clear both to `""` whenever a later iteration's Step 5 is clean (or skipped), otherwise Step 6 in that iteration would be driven by the PRIOR iteration's stale failure block and "fix" a failure that no longer exists (external review PR #1215 Finding 1).
       - **Fixer-skip guard (5a)**: in PR mode, skip Steps 6.1/6.2/6.3 only when Step 3 (build), Step 4 (interfaces) AND Step 5 (tests) ALL reported success — skipping solely on a clean Step 5 lets build/interface failures go un-fixed and burns iterations. Non-PR mode keeps the legacy behaviour (fixer always runs).
       - **Scope guard (Bug 2)**: BEFORE the push, build `pr_file_set` from the UNION of (a) `pr_metadata["api_changed_files_full"]` when present (this is the unbounded list written by `_format_pr_changed_files_for_prompt`), falling back to the truncated `pr_metadata["api_changed_files"]` preview when the full list is unavailable, AND (b) `context["pr_scope_changed_files"]` (the local merge-base diff). The local fallback is REQUIRED — round-8 Finding 2: when the GitHub PR files API errors out or is rate-limited, the API rows are empty even though the local diff still names every PR-touched file, so an API-only `pr_file_set` would refuse valid edits. Parse `^-\s+([A-Z][A-Z0-9]*):\s*(.+?)\s*$` per line against the UNION text — uppercase word statuses (`MODIFIED`/`ADDED`/`DELETED`/`COPIED`/`CHANGED`/`RENAMED`) cover the API formatter, short git statuses (`M`/`A`/`D`/`R100`/etc.) cover the local-diff formatter; treat rename rows (`status startswith "R"`, value contains ` -> `) as `old -> new` (add BOTH paths) and filter out the truncation `NOTE:` footer. The scope-allowed set is `pr_file_set | scope_failure_paths | justified_paths_set`, where `scope_failure_paths` are file paths extracted from Step 5's failure output via `r"(?:tests?/|pdd/|src/)[\w/._-]+\.py"` (round-8 Finding 3: the Step 6 prompt explicitly permits edits to failing test files and causally-connected files without an EXPANSION_ITEMS marker, so the scope guard must accept them; the causal guard below remains the backstop for zero-overlap fixes). Parse `EXPANSION_ITEMS:` from Step 6 output as a STRUCTURED allowlist via `_parse_expansion_items` — the marker counts only when BOTH a non-empty path list AND a per-marker causal justification are present. The justification can be inline (after `— reason` / `because …` / `reason:` separator on the same line) OR on a trailing prose line that carries SEMANTIC content: a `Justification:`/`Reason:`/`Because:`/`Rationale:`/`Why:` prefix, a mention of the marker's own paths (full path or basename), or a causal keyword (`because`, `broken by`, `caused by`, `depends on`, `required by`, `needed for`, `needed because`, `blocked by`, `fails because`, `breaks because`, `due to`, `triggered by`, `imports`, `uses`, `regression in`). Bare indentation or bullets without semantic content do NOT qualify (round-7 Finding 1) — `EXPANSION_ITEMS: plugins/x.py` followed by `  All done.` or `- All done.` MUST NOT justify the path. A bare `EXPANSION_ITEMS:` marker, a `none`/`n/a` payload, or a list of paths with no justification MUST NOT disable the scope refusal. Only subtract a path from `out_of_scope` when it is in the scope-allowed set. If any working-tree change is still out of scope, refuse the push, write `.pdd/checkup-pr-{N}/scope-guard-refusal.txt`, post the canonical Step 7 report, and return `(False, …)`. The previous narrow regex `r"[-+M ]+:\s*(.+)"` did NOT match the real API format and silently rejected every fixer change.
       - **Causal-connection guard (Bug 3)**: when Step 5 returned `FAILED:`, build the "ok set" as the UNION of `pr_file_set`, file paths mentioned in Step 5 output (regex `r"(?:tests?/|pdd/|src/)[\w/._-]+\.py"`), and any `EXPANSION_ITEMS:` paths declared by the fixer. Only refuse when the local fixer files have ZERO overlap with that union — a `tests/test_main.py` failure fixed by editing `pdd/main.py` is the expected pattern and MUST be allowed when `pdd/main.py` is in the PR's changed-file set. On refusal write `.pdd/checkup-pr-{N}/causal-connection-refusal.txt`, post the canonical Step 7 report, and return `(False, …)`.
       - **Clean-run convergence (Bug 5b)**: when the registry/prompt-source guards pass but the working tree has no changes, do NOT short-circuit before finalization. Skip the actual `_commit_and_push_if_changed` call (treat it as `push_ok=True, push_message="No changes to push."`) but still flow through Checkpoint D (PR-head freshness against `_git_rev_parse_head(worktree)`), the outer `clear_workflow_state(...)` at function exit, and `_post_pr_mode_final_report`. A clean PR run must leave no stale `.pdd/checkup-state/checkup_state_{N}.json` behind and must not publish a clean verdict without the final freshness lease. The terminal-success `clear_workflow_state(...)` returns a bool; because `load_workflow_state` prefers the GitHub state comment over local state, a remote clear that cannot be confirmed (e.g. a token without comment-delete/edit scope) would let the NEXT run resume from this completed state instead of rerunning verification. The orchestrator MUST capture that bool and, when false, append a cleanup warning to the returned message (and print it when not quiet) — the checkup itself succeeded so this is a warning, NOT a verdict flip (external review PR #1215 Finding 2).
       - **Clean-run side-effect refusal (Bug 5b / round-3)**: track a `fixer_invoked` flag that flips True only when Steps 6.1/6.2/6.3 actually execute. When Steps 3/4/5 all reported clean the fixer is skipped — and any dirty files left in the worktree are side effects from non-fixer steps (Step 7 tooling, transient agent edits, etc.). Even when those files happen to be in-scope, refuse the commit/push, write `.pdd/checkup-pr-{N}/clean-run-side-effect-refusal.txt`, post the canonical Step 7 report, and return `(False, …)`. Pushing them would recreate the non-convergent clean-run failure where each rerun publishes a new "checkup fix" commit nobody asked for.
       - **Pre-push diff size sanity gate (round-3 Finding 5 / round-9 Finding 2)**: before calling `_commit_and_push_if_changed`, count per-path added lines across uncommitted + untracked files via `git diff --numstat` plus untracked-file line counts (helper `_diff_size_added_lines_by_path` returning `Dict[path, added]`; `_diff_size_added_lines` is a thin wrapper that sums the values). When the total exceeds `DIFF_SIZE_ADDED_LOC_LIMIT` (default 800; override via the `PDD_CHECKUP_DIFF_LOC_LIMIT` env var; the value `0` disables the gate entirely — only an UNPARSEABLE value falls back to the default), refuse the push UNLESS every OVERSIZED dirty path is covered by its OWN justified `EXPANSION_ITEMS:` entry. A path is "oversized" when its individual added lines meet `OVERSIZED_PATH_ADDED_LOC_FLOOR` (default 50) — small companion files (e.g. a 5-line test update next to a 600-line refactor) are exempt from the per-path coverage requirement. If the total is over the limit but NO single path is oversized (a death-by-a-thousand-cuts diff), fall back to the original strict rule and require every changed path to be covered, so diffuse runaway diffs are still blocked. Use the same `_parse_expansion_items` parse the scope guard uses (per-path `justified_paths` set); a sibling marker's justification does NOT wave the size gate through for an oversized path that lacks its own causal reason. Write `.pdd/checkup-pr-{N}/diff-size-guard-refusal.txt`, post the canonical Step 7 report, and return `(False, …)`. The size gate fail-degrades to "do not refuse" on git-probe failure so a flaky subprocess cannot block legitimate fixes.
       - **Step 5 verification-skipped refusal (round-9 #1 / round-10 #1+#2+#3)**: parse `failure_signal.status` into three states — `pass`/`ok`/`success`/`passed`/`clean` ⇒ logically clean; `skipped`/`skip`/`no_tests`/`n/a`/`n_a` ⇒ verification did not run (third state, independent of provider success); everything else (including `fail`/`error`/`failed`/`failure`, an empty/missing status, OR a missing block) ⇒ logical failure (fail closed — round-8 Finding 1). The fixer-skip guard treats both "clean" and "skipped" as not-running-the-fixer (there's no failure to act on). The skipped state is detected from the parsed status REGARDLESS of `_run_single_step`'s provider success flag (round-10 #1: an agent can emit a coherent `status: skipped` block even when its provider call timed out, and we still know tests did not run). The pre-push gate refuses ANY commit/push when the status is skipped — including the no-changes path (round-10 #2: returning "Checkup complete" on a clean worktree when tests never ran misleads the user into thinking the PR was verified). At the gate, RE-DERIVE the skipped state from the persisted `step_outputs["5"]` via a helper that re-parses the `failure_signal` block (stripping a leading `"FAILED: "` prefix if present) rather than trusting `context["step5_verification_skipped"]` alone — `context` is NOT part of the saved workflow state, so a mid-loop interruption can resume with the cached Step 5 skipped block but an empty context cache (round-10 #3); the context value remains a useful in-process hint but must not be the source of truth. The refusal writes `.pdd/checkup-pr-{N}/verification-skipped-refusal.txt`, posts the canonical Step 7 report, and returns `(False, …)` with a message tuned to the dirty/clean case ("Refusing to push fixer/tooling changes …" vs. "The worktree is clean … but the checkup did NOT verify the PR's tests pass — refusing to report success").
       - **--no-fix --pr Step 5 early refusal (round-12/14/15/17 / pass-17)**: in `--no-fix --pr` mode, after the Steps-3/4/5 linear loop completes (whether step 5 ran this session or was skipped via resume), parse `step_outputs["5"]` with the same three-state parse above. Do NOT guard the parse on the raw output being truthy — an EMPTY/missing Step 5 output is itself a fail-closed condition (no test evidence), and parsing `""` yields a missing block that routes to the logical-failure branch (pass-17 Finding 1: a provider that returns success with empty Step 5 output must not slip past the gate as a verified result). A skipped status writes `.pdd/checkup-pr-{N}/nofix-step5-skipped-refusal.txt`, calls `_post_pr_mode_final_report(refusal_message)` to post the refusal as the terminal status comment to the PR and issue threads, calls `clear_workflow_state(...)` to discard the saved cache so the next rerun starts fresh and reruns Step 5 rather than replaying the stale skipped output, and returns `(False, f"{refusal_message}{post_suffix}", …)` before Step 7 runs. A logical failure (status fail/error/empty/missing block) follows the same write-artifact → post-final-report → clear-state → return pattern. Both paths MUST call `_post_pr_mode_final_report` before returning — skipping it leaves GitHub PR/issue threads without a terminal status comment. Both paths MUST call `clear_workflow_state` before returning — skipping it causes stale-cache replay (the same refusal fires on every rerun without re-running Step 5) and duplicate final-report comments when GitHub state is enabled. Both paths refuse before Step 7 because a "clean" Step 7 verdict without test evidence would mislead the user. Non-PR no-fix runs (issue mode) are unaffected. The check MUST read from `step_outputs["5"]` (not only `context["step5_output"]`) so a resumed run whose Step 5 was skipped by `start_step` still applies the contract — `context` is not persisted across process boundaries.
    3. Ensure process isolation by creating and operating within a git worktree for all fix-related steps (Steps 6-8). The worktree must include both uncommitted changes and untracked files from the main repository.
    4. Provide robust resume support by persisting the workflow state (last completed step, outputs, costs, worktree path, AND `mode` ∈ {"issue", "pr"}, AND `pr_number`, `pr_owner`, `pr_repo`, `pr_head_sha` when in PR mode) to a local `.pdd/checkup-state` directory and optionally to GitHub comments. When loading state, validate four identity axes before reuse: (a) `mode` matches the current invocation, (b) `pr_number` matches when both runs are PR-mode, (c) `pr_owner/pr_repo` matches when both are present, (d) `pr_head_sha` is non-empty on both the cached state and current PR metadata and the values are equal. ANY mismatch or missing PR head SHA discards the cached state and forces a fresh setup — the same `issue_number` can verify different PRs over time, and reusing a stale `.pdd/worktrees/checkup-pr-A` path during a verification of PR B silently runs all subsequent steps against the wrong code. When the saved worktree path is missing on resume, recreate it via the SAME helper that originally built it: `_setup_pr_worktree(...)` for PR mode (using saved `pr_owner/pr_repo/pr_number`), `_setup_worktree(...)` for issue mode. Calling the issue-mode helper on a PR-mode resume would silently rebuild from HEAD instead of the PR head. Additionally, a loaded state whose run already COMPLETED (its `last_completed_step`, after the FAILED-step correction, is the terminal step `STEP_ORDER[-1]`) MUST be discarded and re-run from scratch when no `start_step_override` is given (external review PR #1215 Finding 2). The terminal `clear_workflow_state(...)` is best-effort and `load_workflow_state` prefers the GitHub state comment over local state, so a remote clear that failed (e.g. a token without comment-delete/edit scope) would otherwise let the next run resume past the final step, skip every step, and replay the cached Step 7 verdict as `Checkup complete` without re-verifying the current PR head. On discard, reset `last_completed_step = 0` (so `start_step` resolves to step 1) but PRESERVE `github_comment_id = loaded_gh_id` so the fresh run PATCHes the lingering state comment instead of creating a duplicate.
    5. Handle fractional steps (e.g., 6.1, 6.2) for internal logic and template loading, while mapping them to user-friendly labels (e.g., 6a, 6b) in the console output.
    6. Support a `--no-fix` mode which runs analysis steps (1-5) and verification (7) linearly without creating worktrees or PRs.
    7. Support a PR-verification mode (orchestrator parameters `pr_url`, `pr_owner`, `pr_repo`, `pr_number`). When `pr_mode` is true:
       - **Optional source issue (#1292)**: derive `has_issue = bool((issue_url or "").strip())`. When `has_issue` is False the PR has no source issue and is reviewed on its own merits. `run_agentic_checkup` aliases `repo_owner`/`repo_name`/`issue_number` to the PR (so the comment/state thread is the PR) and passes empty `issue_url`/`issue_content`/`issue_title`. In the per-step `context` dict, set `"has_issue"` to `"true"`/`"false"` (keep the empty issue fields as empty strings, never the literal `"None"`, and keep `issue_number` as the PR number so step prompts have a postable thread). The Step 7 verdict gate `_step7_passed(step7_output, pr_mode, has_issue=True)` enforces the `issue_aligned is True` requirement ONLY when `pr_mode AND has_issue`; with no issue the alignment gate is dropped and the verdict rests on code findings alone (no unfixed `critical` issues). Pass `has_issue` at every `_step7_passed` call site. The `has_issue` parameter defaults to `True` so any unthreaded call preserves the legacy alignment gate. With a real issue, behaviour is byte-for-byte unchanged.
       - Set up the worktree via `_setup_pr_worktree(cwd, pr_owner, pr_repo, pr_number, quiet)` BEFORE Step 1 so all subsequent steps see the PR's code, not HEAD.
       - IMMEDIATELY after `_setup_pr_worktree` (and again on resume after restoring the worktree path), call `_refresh_pr_context_from_worktree(context, worktree_path)` to overwrite `context["project_root"]`, `context["architecture_json"]`, and `context["pddrc_content"]` with values loaded from the PR worktree. `run_agentic_checkup` loaded these from the pre-worktree `cwd` and passed them into the orchestrator; without the refresh, prompts audit stale architecture/config and miss PR-introduced changes to architecture.json or `.pddrc` (round-5 Finding 3). The parent `cwd` itself stays unchanged — gh CLI auth and workflow-state persistence run against the original checkout.
       - After the PR worktree is available, refresh the PR base branch into a dedicated local tracking ref, then derive a concise merge-base changed-file summary and store it in `context["pr_changed_files"]` so Step 5 and Step 7 can run PR-scoped tests before attempting any full-suite command. Use local git (`git diff --name-status --find-renames <refreshed-pr-base>...HEAD`) against that refreshed ref. Never use stale `origin/<base>` when PR metadata is available, and never fall back to `HEAD~1`; on multi-commit PRs that silently collapses scope to the last commit. If the PR base cannot be refreshed locally, store an explanatory unavailable string so prompts stay well-formed while agents test conservatively.
       - Resolve the PR's source repo via `pr_owner/pr_repo` (NOT a hardcoded `origin`): walk `git remote -v` looking for a remote whose URL matches `pr_owner/pr_repo`; if none, fetch via the explicit URL `https://github.com/{pr_owner}/{pr_repo}.git pull/{pr_number}/head:{branch_name}`. This is what makes fork-PR verification actually work — a clone of `myfork/repo` cannot fetch `pull/N/head` from `origin` when the PR lives on `upstream/repo`.
       - In full fix mode (`no_fix=False`), run Steps 1-7 against the PR worktree. After the fix/verify loop, commit eligible generated changes with the bot identity and push them back to the PR head branch using PR metadata (`head.repo.clone_url`, `head.ref`, `head.repo.owner.login`, `head.repo.name`). Missing metadata or push failure is a hard failure because fixes must not remain silently local.
       - Step 7 must not post GitHub comments in PR mode — this applies to BOTH the Step 7 agent prompt (which suppresses its own commenting) AND the orchestrator's per-step comment helper: `_handle_step_result` posts a trusted per-step issue comment for every successful step via `post_step_comment_once`, but it MUST skip that per-step post for Step 7 when `pr_mode` is set, otherwise the issue thread gets duplicate Step 7 reporting — the per-step comment AND the canonical final report (external review PR #1215 Finding 3). Earlier steps' progress comments and issue-mode Step 7 comments are unaffected. **No-issue PR mode (#1292)**: when `pr_mode` is set but `has_issue` is False, the per-step comment thread IS the PR (`issue_number == pr_number`), so `_handle_step_result` MUST suppress ALL per-step progress comments (not just Step 7) — otherwise every step floods the PR thread. The single canonical final report still posts to the PR. Additionally, `_post_pr_mode_final_report` MUST skip its second issue-thread `post_step_comment` when `has_issue` is False (it would only duplicate the PR-thread `post_pr_comment`); treat that skipped post as success. The orchestrator owns posting the canonical PR/issue final report and MUST post it on every PR-mode terminal path (gate pass after push, gate fail, max-iteration exhaustion, registry/prompt-source guard refusals, push failure, post-push reverify abort, `--no-fix` gate pass/fail, AND the new `--no-fix --pr` early Step 5 refusals). For the early Step 5 refusal paths (skipped/failing step 5 before Step 7 runs), call `_post_pr_mode_final_report(refusal_message)` — pass the refusal string as the "step 7 output"; the function will sanitize and post it as the terminal status comment. `_post_pr_mode_final_report` returns a `status_suffix` string — empty when both posts succeeded, otherwise containing a pointer to `.pdd/checkup-pr-<n>/final-report.md`. Callers MUST append the suffix to whatever message they return so pdd-issue/pdd_cloud surfaces show the partial-post condition. The helper persists `step_outputs["pr_post_status"]` for state inspection. Comment-post failures MUST NOT flip the gate outcome — gh / network flakiness is independent of code-verification truth (round-5 Finding 4).
       - Skip Step 8 entirely (the PR already exists; the job is to verify and improve it, not open another).
       - **PR-head freshness lease (issue #1116)**: in PR fix mode (not `--no-fix`), bound auto-rerun when the remote PR head advances mid-checkup. Cap restarts at `MAX_PR_HEAD_REFRESHES = 2`. Four freshness checkpoints raise an internal `_PRHeadAdvancedRestart` exception caught by the outer wrapper:
         - **Checkpoint A**: after Step 7's gate passes (`_step7_passed` returns True) but BEFORE the guards-and-push block. Re-fetch PR metadata; if `head_sha` differs from the entry SHA captured at PR-mode start, raise restart.
         - **Checkpoint A2**: after the guards-and-push block's `_fetch_pr_metadata` call but BEFORE the registry/prompt-source guard checks. The two guards each post the canonical Step 7 verdict on refusal; if the head moved between Checkpoint A and now, that verdict belongs to the OLD head. Reuse the just-fetched `pr_metadata["head_sha"]` (no extra GitHub call) and raise restart on mismatch.
         - **Checkpoint B**: when `_commit_and_push_if_changed` returns `(False, push_message)` AND the message indicates a remote-advance-related failure ("Failed to rebase fixes onto updated PR branch", "Failed to refresh PR branch before retrying push", "Failed to reset to original fixer commit before rebase", or generic "Failed to push fixes to PR branch: …" whose embedded git stderr matches `_is_remote_advanced_push_error`). Re-fetch metadata; raise restart only when the fresh `head_sha` actually differs from the entry SHA (auth/network errors must not consume budget).
         - **Checkpoint D**: after EVERY successful `_commit_and_push_if_changed` return — normal push, post-rebase reverify-passed, AND no-change variants ("No changes to push.", "No eligible changes to push."). The check must happen unconditionally on the success path because the round-1 narrow filter on no-change messages left plain-success and rebase-success paths open to a stale verdict when a third party landed commits AFTER our push but BEFORE `_post_pr_mode_final_report`. Baseline is `_git_rev_parse_head(worktree_path)` (the local pushed SHA) — NOT `current_pr_head_sha`. After a real push the remote head moves BECAUSE of us; comparing fresh against entry would false-positive every push. Local HEAD equals our pushed commit on normal/rebase paths and equals entry SHA on the no-change path, so a single Checkpoint D subsumes the round-1 Checkpoint C. Raise restart on mismatch.
       - All checkpoints fail-degrade to current behavior when their baseline SHA is empty or the fresh refetch yields empty — the lease never short-circuits on transient `_fetch_pr_metadata` / `_git_rev_parse_head` failures.
       - **Fix-mode entry-SHA fail-closed**: when fix mode (`no_fix=False`) enters PR mode and the entry `_fetch_pr_metadata` returns an empty `head_sha`, the orchestrator MUST fail-closed immediately — no Step 7, no worktree fix loop, no push. Every fix-mode checkpoint gates on a non-empty `current_pr_head_sha`; without that baseline the entire lease silently disables, opening the same stale-verdict hole the lease was built to close. Symmetric with the `--no-fix` post-Step-7 fail-closed below. Return shape: `(False, "Could not determine entry PR head SHA for PR #N; fix-mode freshness lease requires a baseline. Rerun pdd checkup --pr.", total_cost, last_model_used)`.
       - The public `run_agentic_checkup_orchestrator` is a thin wrapper around an internal `_run_agentic_checkup_orchestrator_inner` that contains the existing 8-step body. Non-PR mode is pass-through. PR mode loops around the inner, catches `_PRHeadAdvancedRestart`, and:
         - Accumulates `cost_so_far` from each iteration into a cumulative return cost.
         - Calls `clear_workflow_state(...)` (best-effort try/except) so a flaky next `_fetch_pr_metadata` returning the OLD SHA cannot defeat the rerun via the resume-state identity guard. The restart exception already proves the head advanced; don't depend on a fresh fetch to re-prove it.
         - Increments and persists a refresh counter at `.pdd/checkup-pr-{pr_number}/pr_head_refreshes` (single int, best-effort I/O) so a Ctrl-C + manual rerun cannot bypass the bound. The sidecar lives OUTSIDE the workflow-state dir so `clear_workflow_state` never deletes it.
         - When `refresh_count >= MAX_PR_HEAD_REFRESHES`, returns failure with a diagnostic that lists every observed `old_sha->new_sha` transition and cites `max_pr_head_refreshes=2`.
         - On clean inner return (success OR failure), removes the sidecar so the next checkup on this PR starts with a full budget.
       - `--no-fix` mode does NOT consume restart budget. The fix-mode checkpoints all guard with `not no_fix`. However, `--no-fix --pr` mode DOES perform its own one-shot head-freshness check: after Step 7's gate passes, refetch the PR head SHA. Fail-closed on THREE conditions (no budget consumed): (a) the fresh SHA differs from the entry SHA (advance confirmed), (b) the refetch fails / returns an empty SHA (freshness unknown after the run), or (c) the entry SHA was empty / unknown when we entered PR mode (freshness unknown before the run). Any one of the three returns `success=False` with a diagnostic, and posts a report body that includes the downgrade reason prepended to the Step 7 output via a `**Verdict downgraded — unverified:**` banner (so the PR/issue thread shows WHY the verdict was invalidated). `_finalize`'s SHA-mismatch downgrade only runs under `--review-loop`, NOT plain `--no-fix --pr`, so the orchestrator owns this guardrail.
       - The lease NEVER force-pushes. `_commit_and_push_if_changed`'s return shape stays `(bool, str)`. `_run_final_checkup_on_pr` in `agentic_e2e_fix_orchestrator.py` remains the outer safety net and is NOT modified by this fix.
       - `_PRHeadAdvancedRestart` carries a `step_comments: Set[int]` field. Every raise site passes the current `step_comments_set`. The outer wrapper preserves this across restart iterations in `preserved_step_comments: Set[int]` and passes it back into the next inner call via `_carried_step_comments: Optional[Set[int]] = None`. When the inner starts with `state is None`, it initialises `step_comments_set` from `_carried_step_comments` (if provided) instead of an empty set, so per-step issue comments are not re-posted after `clear_workflow_state` wipes the persisted field.
       - `_run_agentic_checkup_orchestrator_inner` accepts two additional private kwargs set only by the outer wrapper on restart iterations: `_force_skip_state_load: bool = False` (when True, sets `state = None, loaded_gh_id = None` without calling `load_workflow_state`, defeating any silent GitHub DELETE failure that leaves stale state loadable) and `_carried_step_comments: Optional[Set[int]] = None` (described above). The outer sets `_force_skip_state_load = (refresh_count > 0)` and `_carried_step_comments = preserved_step_comments if refresh_count > 0 else None`.
    8. Implement per-step timeouts and error handling, including a mechanism to abort if agent providers fail consecutively. Classify user-facing aborts as agent execution timeouts only for runner/process timeout wording such as `Timeout expired`, `TimeoutExpired`, `Agent timed out`, or `Step <n> timed out`; generic provider/request/network timeout wording must remain provider failure wording.
    9. **Trusted Step-Comment Flow**: The orchestrator owns visible per-step `## Step N/8:` comments on the GitHub issue, posted via `gh issue comment` with trusted PDD credentials. Step prompts MUST NOT call `gh issue comment` themselves for successful step progress — they emit a single `<step_report>...</step_report>` block in their final response and the orchestrator extracts and posts it once.
        - Import from `pdd.agentic_common`: `extract_step_report(step_output) -> Optional[str]`, `post_step_comment_once(*, repo_owner, repo_name, issue_number, step_num: int, body: str, posted_steps: Set[int], cwd) -> bool`, and `normalize_step_comments_state(raw) -> Set[int]`.
        - **State shape**: `state["step_comments"]` persists as a sorted `List[int]` on disk; hydrate to `Set[int]` via `normalize_step_comments_state` on resume; persist back as a sorted list via `_build_state(..., step_comments=sorted(step_comments_set))` on every save (success, hard-stop, abort).
        - **Composite-key encoding (REQUIRED — helper is `Set[int]`-typed)**: the checkup workflow has fractional steps (6.1, 6.2, 6.3) and an iterated fix-verify loop. Project each (step_num, iteration) tuple to a deterministic non-negative int via `iteration * 10000 + int(round(step_num * 10))`. Use `iteration=1` for non-iterative steps (1, 2, 8); pass the actual `fix_verify_iteration` for the loop-body steps (3, 4, 5, 6.1, 6.2, 6.3, 7).
        - **Posting protocol** inside `_handle_step_result`: when `description` is provided AND the step succeeded, compute `report_body = extract_step_report(step_output)`; if `None`, use a short fallback body saying the step completed and raw output is retained in workflow state. Build `f"## Step {step_num}/8: {description}\n\n{report_body}"` and call `post_step_comment_once(...)` with the composite key. Any exception MUST be log-and-continue (never raise into the orchestrator loop).
        - **PR-mode**: in PR-verification mode the trusted helper still posts to the GitHub *issue* thread (`post_step_comment_once` calls `gh issue comment`). It does NOT replace the Step 7 PR-thread comment routing (`gh pr comment`).
        - **Relationship to legacy `post_step_comment`**: hard-stop / failure comments continue to flow through the legacy helper unchanged. `post_step_comment_once` is strictly additive — it covers the success-comment case that previously had no first-party posting path.

